 lake, where they were then shown hopping into a rowing boat.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZWYyNzNiNDQtM2RiYi00NmYzLTk4YmUtODQyY2M4YzE2MGE2XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('John Lennon: Oh My Love',6.3,NULL,3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYjU3YTQ2YjEtY2VjYy00YjUwLWE0YjgtMjA0OWUzYzIwNjAxXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('John Lennon: Oh Yoko!',5.9,NULL,6,NULL,1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('Yoko Ono: Don\'t Count the Waves',NULL,NULL,6,NULL,1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL),('John Lennon: Imagine',7.8,'John and Yoko are shown walking in the countryside, in bleak weather. They arrive in an empty house and while Yoko opens the windows, John sits at the piano, plays and sings.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYmM5MWQwMDQtMGRjOC00NTViLTk5MzEtZTZlNGVmZTQ5Yzc5XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNDMxMTc5OTE@.jpg',1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('Yoko Ono: Mrs. Lennon',NULL,'A music video was made for this song which was premiered on \"The Dick Cavett Show\" on 11 September 1971 when John Lennon and Yoko Ono were guests on the programme.(The video is introduced at approximately the 39:24 mark). Film of \"Mrs. Lennon\" depicting the couple walking around their Ascot mansion was included in the 1972 television film Imagine.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNWU5YTU2MTUtN2MyNS00YWY5LTljYzctYjIzMDRkOGM1YjhmXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMTE3MjAyODEz.jpg',1971,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL),('Apotheosis',4.4,'Yoko Ono fixed a camera, pointing downward, to a weather balloon and released it. As the balloon begins its ascent, we see Ono and husband John Lennon sitting on a Central Park bench. Several minutes into the film, the balloon enters a bank of clouds, eradicating the image for several more minutes, when it emerges from the clouds, the view from above them is spectacular. This single-reel movie ends at the point when the camera ran out of film.',18,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNTdjZjE0ODItZmQwNi00ZjU1LWFkYjAtZTIwYzdkYjZlNWRkXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMDM0MzU2NA@@.jpg',1970,'Short','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,'John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,'Nicholas D. Knowland',NULL),('The Beatles: The Long and Winding Road',7.1,'The DVD track is from the film Let It Be, with footage being used from the same recording sessions as \"Let It Be\". The only exception with both videos is that the audio from the sessions was used in this video instead of the one for \"Let It Be\".',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNjRkZGM1ZGItZDMxZC00ZDU0LTg1NjQtOTAxZWU0NmRmZDRiXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1970,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Let It Be',7.9,'\"Let It Be\" is a song by the English rock band the Beatles, released in March 1970 as a single, and (in an alternate mix) as the title track of their album Let It Be. It was their final single before McCartney announced his departure from the band. The single used the same cover photographs as the Let It Be album, and was originally released on 6 March 1970. Film of the Beatles performance was shown on the Ed Sullivan Show on February 15, 1970.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNDFjMzYyNjEtNjdkNi00MDM1LWI5YjItZDRkMDY2YWM4MmNlXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1970,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('John Lennon, Ono and the Plastic Ono Band: Instant Karma!',5.4,'John and The Plastic Ono Band, filmed for BBC 1\'s \"Top of the Pops\" on 11 February 1970.',4,NULL,1970,'Short, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('John Lennon & The Plastic Ono Band: Give Peace a Chance - Version 1',6.2,'\'Give Peace a Chance\' is an anti-war song written by John Lennon and recorded with the participation of a small group of friends in a performance with Yoko Ono in a hotel room in Montreal, Quebec, Canada.',6,NULL,1969,'Short, Music','English','John Lennon, Yoko Ono',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('Plastic Ono Band: Cold Turkey - First Version',4.5,NULL,4,NULL,1969,'Short, Music','English','D.A. Pennebaker',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Something',7.8,'The promotional video for \"Something\" was shot shortly after Lennon had privately announced that he was leaving the band. By this time, the individual Beatles had drawn apart and so the film consisted of separate clips of each Beatle walking around his home, accompanied by his wife, edited together.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMjQ0Nzg3MDQtNzlmOS00M2ViLWIwYmItMjE4MmNmYTAzM2FmXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1969,'Short, Music','English','Neil Aspinall',NULL,NULL,'George Harrison',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: The Ballad of John and Yoko',6.9,NULL,3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMmFiZTdlMzctNjBhNS00MzkyLWJiNjQtYWEwMDZlMzk4ZDE3XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1969,'Short, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Get Back',9,'In January 1969 The Beatles entered the recording studio to write and rehearse the songs for their album \'Let It Be\'. They are on a very tight schedule as they intend to debut the songs in a live performance within a few weeks. The live performance will be the album. A camera crew is recording everything that goes on in the studio in order to make a film out of the experience. This is an edited version of what they captured.',468,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNjMxMjE5ZTEtMjgyOC00ODM4LWJjZDAtMjcwZDBlNzZhZTkyXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMDM2NDM2MQ@@.jpg',2021,'Documentary, Biography, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Don\'t Let Me Down',7.7,'\"Don\'t Let Me Down\" is a song by the Beatles (with Billy Preston), recorded in 1969 during the Let It Be sessions. It was written by John Lennon and credited to Lennon-McCartney. The Beatles performed \"Don\'t Let Me Down\" during their rooftop concert of 30 January 1969. The performance was included in the Let It Be (1970) film, which was directed by Michael Lindsay-Hogg.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZGI4ZmEzYTctYzRhNC00NDVlLWFjNDAtMTkxZDQ3MmJlMThkXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1969,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Yellow Submarine',7.8,'The Beatles agree to accompany Captain Fred in his Yellow Submarine and go to Pepperland to free it from the music hating Blue Meanies.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZTM0NTk5OTUtMDNhNy00Mzc2LTg0YjAtMTgyNzVmODdiNjliXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNTM3MDMyMDQ@.jpg',1968,'Animation, Short, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Dirty Mac: Yer Blues',NULL,'The Dirty Mac performing \"Yer Blues\" From The Rolling Stones Rock and Roll Circus.',4,NULL,1968,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Rolling Stones: Sympathy for the Devil',6.2,'Godard\'s documentation of late 1960s Western counter-culture, examining the Black Panthers, referring to works by LeRoi Jones and Eldridge Cleaver. Other notable subjects are the role of news media, the mediated image, a growing technocratic society, women\'s liberation, the May revolt in France and the power of language. Cutting between three major scenes, including the Rolling Stones in the studio, the film is visually intercut with Eve Democracy (Wiazemsky) using graffiti which amalgamates organisations, corporations and ideologies. Godard also examines the role of the revolutionary within Western culture. Although he believes Western culture needs to be destroyed, it can only be done so by the rejection of intellectualisation. \"There is only one way to be an intellectual revolutionary, and that is to give up being an intellectual\"',111,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZmQ4NzBlODgtMTZlYi00YTM1LWE1MGMtMzQ5NWIwNWYxNzE1XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMzIzNDU1NTY@.jpg',1968,'Documentary, Music','English','Jean-Luc Godard','Jean-Luc Godard','Eleni Collard, Michael Pearson, Iain Quarrier',NULL,'Anthony B. Richmond','Kenneth F. Rowles'),('Two Virgins',5,'Psychedelia and love images blended and interacting.',19,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BODBhMjJhNmQtZDgzNy00MTNkLWFjN2EtNTZlOTgzOGExMDgyXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNzI4MDMyMTU@.jpg',1968,'Short',NULL,'John Lennon, Yoko Ono','John Lennon, Yoko Ono','John Lennon, Yoko Ono','Yoko Ono','William Wareing',NULL),('The Beatles: Revolution',7.6,'Video promo for The Beatles: Revolution.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYzA4MTU2MjYtZWE4YS00MjViLTg0MDYtNjk4MTA3NWY5ZGRjXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1968,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Hey Jude',7.9,'The Beatles hired Michael Lindsay-Hogg to shoot a promotional clip for \"Hey Jude\", after he had previously directed a clip for \"Paperback Writer\" in 1966. They settled on the idea of shooting with a live, albeit controlled, audience. In the clip, the Beatles are first seen by themselves, performing the initial chorus and verses, and then are joined by the audience who appear as the last chorus concludes and coda begins; the audience sings and claps along with the Beatles through the song\'s conclusion. Hogg shot the clip at Twickenham Film Studios on 4 September 1968, with McCartney himself designing the set.',8,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZDRiNjliMzYtMzJjNi00ZmQ3LWIyYTAtMGVkMDE4ODVjYjI4XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1968,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Eleanor Rigby',7.2,NULL,2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BM2Y0Y2IxNGEtMWRhNS00Mzg3LWIyNzktZDE5MmU2NTdiYzJhXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1968,'Animation, Short, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('Yellow Submarine',7.4,'When the music-hating Blue Meanies take over Pepperland and freeze everyone within it, including the protectors, Sgt. Pepper\'s Lonely Hearts Club Band, Captain Fred (Lance Percival) and his Yellow Submarine recruit The Beatles to help save Pepperland. Along the way, they fall through the Sea of Time, Sea of Nothing, Sea of Holes, and more. They meet Jeremy Hillary Boob Ph.D. (Dick Emery) and take him with them for the adventure. At Pepperland, The Beatles \"rally the land to rebellion\" and take down the Blue Meanies, the four-headed Meanie dog, and the Dreadful Flying Glove (with the songs \"Sgt. Pepper\'s Lonely Hearts Club Band\", \"With A Little Help From My Friends\", \"Hey Bulldog\", \"All You Need is Love\"). In the end, all four live-action Beatles sing \"All Together Now\".',90,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMGExODFmMjQtZTgxOC00ZDE0LWJmM2MtOTQzM2YzNDZlMzNmL2ltYWdlL2ltYWdlXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNjc1NTYyMjg@.jpg',1968,'Animation, Adventure, Comedy, Fantasy, Musical','English','George Dunning','Lee Minoff, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Lee Minoff, Al Brodax, Jack Mendelsohn, Erich Segal, Roger McGough','Al Brodax, Alan Kozlowski, Mary Ellen Stewart',NULL,NULL,'Brian J. Bishop'),('The Beatles: Lady Madonna - Version 1',6.6,'Two promotional films were made for \"Lady Madonna\", which were syndicated to television broadcasting companies. The material was shot on 11 February 1968 in Abbey Road Studios and was distributed by NEMS Enterprises to US and UK TV stations.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZjY5ZTc1ZTItYmM3MC00YWI0LWE3NDAtN2M3NDIwZTBhNDJjXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1968,'Short, Music','English','Tony Bramwell',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Lady Madonna - Version 2',6.5,'Two promotional films were made for \"Lady Madonna\", which were syndicated to television broadcasting companies. The material was shot on 11 February 1968 in Abbey Road Studios and was distributed by NEMS Enterprises to US and UK TV stations.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMWZiNTUyZjMtMTczOS00YzEzLWFlMTctYTNmMDQyMDliNTY5XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1968,'Short, Music','English','Tony Bramwell',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: A Day in the Life',8,'\"A Day in the Life\" is a song by the English rock band the Beatles that was released as the final track of their 1967 album Sgt. Pepper\'s Lonely Hearts Club Band. Credited to Lennon-McCartney, the verses were written mainly by John Lennon, with Paul McCartney primarily contributing the song\'s middle section. Lennon\'s lyrics were inspired by contemporary newspaper articles, including a report on the death of Guinness heir Tara Browne. The recording includes two passages of orchestral glissandos that were partly improvised in the avant-garde style.',5,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYTAzZmY2MmEtZmFhZS00YTAyLTllZDItODY3NjA2ZjI2ZTUxXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','The Beatles',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Strawberry Fields Forever',8,'The Beatles produced a promotional film clip for \"Strawberry Fields Forever\", which served as an early example of what became known as a music video. The film features reverse film effects, stop motion animation, jump-cuts from daytime to night-time, and the Beatles playing and later pouring paint over the upright piano.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BODMzNTIxZmEtMThkNy00MDgzLTlkYjItZDIwY2Y3ZTU4NmQ5XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Peter Goldmann',NULL,'Tony Bramwell','John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('Magical Mystery Tour',6.1,'The Beatles\' first movie since Help. (1965) was largely Sir Paul McCartney\'s project. The story follows a busload of eccentric characters on a magical journey through the English countryside. Rather than a unified narrative, it becomes a series of psychedelic clips promoting various songs including \"The Fool on the Hill\", \"Blue Jay Way\", \"Your Mother Should Know\", \"I Am the Walrus\", and \"Magical Mystery Tour\". The Bonzo Dog Doo-Dah Band are seen in a strip club playing \"Death Cab for Cutie\".',55,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNTVlYzJjMjktZjFhOS00ZTZkLWI0MGQtMDc3MzlhMGVlMjU1XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMTgzOTAxMzA@.jpg',1967,'Comedy, Fantasy, Musical','English','George Harrison, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr, Bernard Knowles','Mal Evans, George Harrison, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr','George Harrison, John Lennon, Gavrik Losey, Paul McCartney, Denis O\'Dell, Ringo Starr','George Harrison, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr','Ringo Starr','Roy Benson'),('The Beatles: Blue Jay Way',6.5,'The Beatles perform the George Harrison-penned song \"Blue Jay Way\", featuring Harrison on lead vocals. The sequence is very dream-like, and features Harrison playing a chalk-drawing of a piano. Meanwhile, we see footage of the band playing football with their hands and playing a cello.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMGEzM2M5NGItMjViNi00YTBjLThiYTMtMDczZGNjNjA4NWIxXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','The Beatles, George Harrison, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: I Am the Walrus',7.7,'Video promo for The Beatles: I Am the Walrus.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZTJkMTQ3ZTQtMTMyZC00YzJlLWJlNjUtMWIyODY2YmY1ZGEwXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','The Beatles, George Harrison, John Lennon, Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Hello, Goodbye - Version 2',6.6,'In the second clip, the Beatles mime to the song dressed in more conventional attire and with the stage backdrop depicting a rural setting.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYmQ3ZWU3ZTQtZGFkNi00Yjk4LWIwMmMtYzUyYjYwMDcyNTcyXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Hello, Goodbye - Version 3',6.5,'The third version combines footage shot during these two scenes with the band playing the song before what Winn terms a \"glittery pastel backdrop\".',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYjVlNGExMGUtZjUxNC00NTM1LTk2MzgtOWVhMGM4OTE2ZDFmXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Hello, Goodbye',7.6,'Filmed on 10 November 1967 at the Saville Theatre in London, the clip was directed by Paul McCartney. It shows the Beatles dressed in their Sgt. Pepper uniforms, apart from a brief cut-away where the group are wearing their 1963-era matching collarless suits. This version shows the Beatles performing the song against a psychedelic backdrop, while over the coda they are joined on the stage by female hula dancers. Starr is seen playing a miniature drum kit and, unusually, Lennon appears without his granny glasses.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNWI0NWZjYjAtY2U2Yi00Y2JlLWI2MjYtY2U5Yzc5YjViNjNmXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('How I Won the War',5.5,'This movie features Beatle John Lennon and Roy Kinnear as ill-fated enlisted men under the inept command of Lieutenant Ernest Goodbody (Michael Crawford). The story unwinds mostly in flashbacks of Lieutenant Goodbody who has lower-class beginnings and education which make him a poor officer who commands one of the worst units of the Army.',109,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYTIwOTRiNTYtMjRiZS00MWY4LTk4YzItZGM5MDg1MWIyZTQwXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNjMwMjk0MTQ@.jpg',1967,'Comedy, War','English','Richard Lester','Patrick Ryan, Charles Wood','Richard Lester, Denis O\'Dell','Ken Thorne','David Watkin','John Victor Smith'),('The Beatles: All You Need Is Love',7.5,'The Beatles (except for Starr, behind his drum kit) were seated on high stools, accompanied by a thirteen-piece orchestra. The band were surrounded by friends and acquaintances seated on the floor, who sang along with the refrain during the fade-out.',4,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BODYwOTI3ZGQtMGQ2NC00ODcyLWE2ZDYtZGNiZTQxNTM5ZDZiXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Derek Burrell-Davis',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Penny Lane',7.7,'The music video for the song was not filmed at Penny Lane, as the Beatles were reluctant to travel to Liverpool. Street scenes were filmed in and around Angel Lane in London\'s East End. The broken sequence of Lennon walking alone was filmed on the King\'s Road (at Markham Square) in Chelsea. The outdoor scenes were filmed at Knole Park in Sevenoaks on 30 January 1967. The promotional film for \"Strawberry Fields Forever\" was also shot at the same location, during the same visit.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMzIxZTUzOTktNmY0Zi00MTc3LTk1NTUtOTA0MzE2ZDM5YjYwXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1967,'Short, Music','English','Peter Goldmann',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Rain',7.4,'The Beatles created three promotional films for \"Rain\" which are considered among the early precursors of music videos.The films were directed by Michael Lindsay-Hogg. One features the Beatles walking and singing in a garden and a greenhouse (filmed 20 May 1966 at Chiswick House in London).',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNTQ0ZWI5ZmEtNDQ1NS00NmNiLThhMjEtMjMxYTAxNTBmNGM3XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1966,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('Not Only... But Also',8.3,'Not Only...But Also, most famously showcased Peter Cook and Dudley Moore in there so-called \'Dagenham dialogues\' in which Pete (a nasal know-all who has utter confidence in his surreal and ill-informed philosophies on life) and Dud (credulous, dim-witted and scruffy) discuss all manner of subjects, bedecked in cloth caps and Macs.',45,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTU0ODcxNTA4Ml5BMl5BanBnXkFtZTcwMzM2MDMyMQ@@.jpg',1965,'Comedy','English',NULL,'Peter Cook, Dudley Moore, Robert Fuest',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Paperback Writer - Version 2',6.3,'On the first day Michael Lindsay-Hogg recorded a colour performance at EMI Studios, for The Ed Sullivan Show, which was shown on 5 June.',3,NULL,1966,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Rain - The Ed Sullivan Show Version',6.9,'The Beatles created three promotional films for \"Rain\" which are considered among the early precursors of music videos.The films were directed by Michael Lindsay-Hogg. One features the band performing on a sound stage (filmed 19 May 1966, one in colour for Ed Sullivan)',3,NULL,1966,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Paperback Writer',7.4,'On 20 May, another colour film was made at Chiswick House in west London.The Beatles mimed to the song, and they were shown in and around the conservatory in the grounds of the house. The clip was first broadcast in black and white on BBC-TV\'s Top of the Pops on 2 June. The 20 May promo clip was included in the Beatles\' 2015 video compilation 1.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTVlMmMzZjEtNWE4YS00ZmY2LTg3MDktZmE4N2FhZDhhYTY1XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1966,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,'Tony Bramwell','John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Rain - B&W Version',6.1,'The Beatles created three promotional films for \"Rain\" which are considered among the early precursors of music videos. The films were directed by Michael Lindsay-Hogg. One features the band performing on a sound stage (filmed 19 May 1966, one in black and white for the UK.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNjkyZWVkZDItMDE0Yi00ZjQ4LTkxZTUtN2Q0ODE1MGY3Mzk4XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1966,'Short, Music','English','Michael Lindsay-Hogg',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Day Tripper - Version 2',6.6,'The Beatles filmed three different music videos, directed by Joe McGrath, on 23 November 1965. These videos, along with a batch of other mimed performances (including the song\'s flip-side, \"We Can Work It Out\"), were meant to be sent to various television music and variety shows, to air on those programs in lieu of personal studio appearances.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTlmNTFkNDUtYWM3ZS00ZDI5LTk4MTUtMDhjYzljZDhmZWJkXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Day Tripper - Version 3',6.3,'The Beatles filmed three different music videos, directed by Joe McGrath, on 23 November 1965. These videos, along with a batch of other mimed performances (including the song\'s flip-side, \"We Can Work It Out\"), were meant to be sent to various television music and variety shows, to air on those programs in lieu of personal studio appearances.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZDVlY2E5MWQtYjdkYy00MjdmLWJlMzMtNTY1YTUwZjJkYjA1XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: We Can Work it Out',7.4,'On Tuesday 23 November 1965 The Beatles were in Twickenham Film Studios to film some promotional videos for their new single We Can Work It Out/Day Tripper. Three versions of We Can Work It Out were made, this one is known as \"We can work it out dark clothes\"',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZGEwNzUxZjktZWU0OC00NDYzLWJiY2YtZDM1MTlmYjdmZjYyXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyMjUyNDk2ODc@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: We Can Work It Out - Version 2',6.7,'Alternate promotional film. Filmed at Twickenham Film Studios, Middlesex, England, 23 November 1965.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTUxZDliNmEtYmIzOC00ZTNhLTlhOGQtZGI5MWU1NjZmYzhhXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: We Can Work It Out - Version 3',6.3,'Another clip shows the group wearing the stage suits from their Shea Stadium performance on 15 August.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMDhjZTlkODYtYjAxYi00NTgxLTg3MzMtODZiODY2ZDBlMzk4XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English',NULL,NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Day Tripper - Version 1',6.5,'The Beatles filmed three different music videos, directed by Joe McGrath, on 23 November 1965. These videos, along with a batch of other mimed performances (including the song\'s flip-side, \"We Can Work It Out\"), were meant to be sent to various television music and variety shows, to air on those programs in lieu of personal studio appearances.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNGUwMmQ5ODUtNTlhMi00ZjU2LThkYjktYjNlYzFhMDk1YjJjXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Help! - Version 2',7.2,'They made another promotional clip of \"Help!\" on 23 November 1965 for inclusion in the year-end recap special of Top of the Pops. Directed by Joseph McGrath, the black-and-white clip shows the group miming to the song while sitting astride a workbench. Starr holds an umbrella overhead throughout the song, which becomes useful as fake snow falls during the final verse.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYjk3NTBmODUtNzExYy00ODlmLTllY2YtODM2NTIxYzc4MDNhXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: I Feel Fine - Version 1',6.7,'Two different music videos directed by Joe McGrath were filmed on 23 November 1965. Both feature various bits of gym equipment. In the first, George sang into a punch-ball while Ringo pedalled on an exercise bike.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNDQyZWYxZDItYzQzOS00Y2UwLTgzNjUtM2QyN2FmMWViZTE1XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: I Feel Fine - Version 2',6.3,'The second version marked the only time a lunch break was filmed, where they all ate fish and chips, while trying to mime to the song.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYzZiZWU0MGEtYzM1Yy00ZTU4LTkzNzItNTMyNTExZWFjYTVkXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Ticket to Ride',7.1,'On 23 November 1965, the Beatles filmed promotional clips for \"Ticket to Ride\" and four other songs.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZmRjNDhlMGItMjE1Ni00OWRkLWEzNDUtNWYwYzM4NDQ2MmQ3XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Joseph McGrath',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: A Hard Day\'s Night',7.4,'Bound for a London show from Liverpool, the Beatles escape a horde of fans.',3,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BYzc2OWRhYzgtODI1NC00YWIxLWE1YjgtOTMwYzFkYWM3ZjYwXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Jean-Christophe Averty',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('The Beatles: Yesterday',7.8,'\"Yesterday\" is a song by the English rock band the Beatles, written by Paul McCartney and credited to Lennon-McCartney. \"Yesterday\" is a melancholy ballad about the break-up of a relationship. The singer nostalgically laments for yesterday when he and his love were together, before she left because of something he said. McCartney is the only member of the Beatles to appear on the track.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNDEwYTFjOTYtOTMzMy00M2JhLTk2NWItYmZmOWJiMTFhYmY0XkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNDE4OTY5NzI@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Tim Kiley',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul McCartney',NULL,NULL),('Help!',7.1,'An Eastern cult discovers that the sacrificial ring is missing. Sir Ringo Starr, drummer of The Beatles has it; sent by the girl (who\'s to be sacrificed) as a gift. Clang, Ahme, Bhuta, and several cult members leave for London to retrieve the ring. After several failed attempts to steal the ring, they confront him in an Indian restaurant. Ringo learns that if he does not return the ring soon, he will become the next sacrifice. Ringo then discovers that the ring is stuck on his finger. Its a race against time; John Lennon, Sir Paul McCartney, and George Harrison try to protect their friend while they\'re all being chased not only by Clang and his minions, but also by two mad scientists and the Chief Inspector of Scotland yard. Will Ringo be saved, or will he be sacrificed?',92,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMjZlNjAyNjItMDEwNy00OTExLWIzOTEtNDI0MTAzMWY4YThmXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyNjUwMzI2NzU@.jpg',1965,'Adventure, Comedy, Musical','English','Richard Lester','Marc Behm, Charles Wood, Marc Behm','Walter Shenson','Paul McCartney, Ken Thorne','David Watkin','John Victor Smith'),('The Beatles: Help! - Version 1',7.6,'The Beatles filmed the title performance for the movie Help. on 22 April 1965. The same footage (without the darts and credits seen in the film sequence) was used as a clip to promote the release of the single. It was shown starting in July 1965 on programmes such as Top of the Pops and Thank Your Lucky Stars.',2,'https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNzgxZGU2ZjAtMjE0OS00ZDE4LThjOWUtNTdhZjM4MTAxOWJiXkEyXkFqcGdeQXVyOTc5MDI5NjE@.jpg',1965,'Short, Music','English','Richard Lester',NULL,NULL,'John Lennon, Paul Mc